{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":37343,"name":"Graham Morrison","username":"degville","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/forum.snapcraft.io/degville/{size}/2021_2.png","created_at":"2018-11-08T17:44:14.094Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse of the \u003ccode\u003esnap\u003c/code\u003e command with a directory has been deprecated in favour of the \u003ccode\u003epack\u003c/code\u003e command.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003eintroduced in snapcraft 2.35\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ccode\u003esnap\u003c/code\u003e command originally served two purposes:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003esnapcraft snap\u003c/code\u003e walked through the entire lifecycle for each part of the project (pull, build, stage, and prime) before finally creating the snap, and\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003esnapcraft snap \u0026lt;directory\u0026gt;\u003c/code\u003e simply created a snap of the provided directory (without involving the lifecycle at all).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis ended up being confusing from the point of view of someone working on an actual snapcraft project.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe new command \u003ccode\u003epack\u003c/code\u003e is much more explicit in that snapcraft is just focusing on assembling the final snap from a valid layout for a given directory.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe new way to create a snap from a directory has the following syntax:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-bash\"\u003esnapcraft pack \u0026lt;directory\u0026gt;\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSee \u003ca href=\"/t/deprecation-notices/8396/2\"\u003eDeprecation notices\u003c/a\u003e  for further announcements.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2018-11-08T17:44:25.805Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":87,"reads":4,"readers_count":3,"score":435.8,"yours